ODE XXVIII.

Horace was a lover of pleasure‚ and had early imbibed the doc- trines of Epicurus, which favored his propensitieS. But in this ode he acknowledges his error in living, as he had, a life of sensu- ality, and in neglecting the duties of religion and the worship of the godS. Some have doubted his sincerity.
